                  <h4><b>RECEPIENT WAITLIST PRIORITIZATION:</b><br>
                    </h4>
                    <p>A single donor may get matched with many number of recipients. Though matching plays a vital role, without prioritization it is difficult to match with the right recipient. <br>
                      The prioritization factors are <br>
                      <b>Medical condition</b><br>
                      It is important to check the medical urgency whether the recipient is in critical condition or not. <br>
                      <b>EPTS (Estimated Post Transplant Survival)</b><br>
                      Computer calculates your score, which ranges from zero to 100. Candidates with a low EPTS, a score closer to zero, would likely have the longest time to benefit from a transplanted kidney.  Candidates with a higher EPTS score, closer to 100, are likely to have less time to benefit with a transplanted kidney. 20% or less – more survival time after transplant. 20% greater – less survival time after transplant. 
                      Per OPTN policy, the EPTS score is derived from the following formula:<br>
